Explain the similarities and differences between client-server and peer to peer architectures (100 words)

Client-server architecture is a model in which a central server provides services to multiple clients. The server manages resources and provides services to clients, which request and receive data from the server. In contrast, peer-to-peer (P2P) architecture is a model in which each device acts as both a client and a server, sharing resources and services with other devices. Similarities between the two architectures include the use of protocols for communication and the ability to share resources. Differences include the centralization of resources in client-server architecture and the decentralization of resources in P2P architecture.

WiFi networks are ideal for stationary devices and applications that require low-latency data transfer, such as online banking and video conferencing.

CPNs are designed to provide high-quality content to users with low latency and high availability.
